{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Agnes Christine Johnston | image = Agnes Johnston - Feb 1919 MPW.jpg | caption = Johnston in 1919 | birth_date = {{birth date|1896|1|11}} | birth_place = [[Swissvale, Pennsylvania]], United States | death_date = {{death date and age|1978|7|19|1896|1|11}} | death_place = [[San Diego, California]], United States | yearsactive = 1915–1948 | occupation = Screenwriter | spouse = [[Frank Dazey]] }}
'''Agnes Christine Johnston''' (January 11, 1896 &ndash; July 19, 1978) was an American [[screenwriter]].
==Biography== Johnston was born in [[Swissvale, Pennsylvania]]. She wrote for 84 films between 1915 and 1948. She had intended to go to college, but was sufficiently proficient in writing scenarios for films following graduating from high school that she ended up taking just a single course in writing plays at Harvard in 1918.<ref name="MPW">{{cite journal |title=Agnes Johnston, Scenarist |journal=Moving Picture World |volume=39 |issue=6 |page=744 |publisher=Chalmers Publishing Company |location=New York City |date=February 8, 1919 |url=https://archive.org/details/movingwor39chal |accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref> When [[Vitagraph Studios]] gave her an assignment to write a scenario for a [[James Oliver Curwood]] novel ''God's Country and the Woman'', she completed the scenario for the [[William Duncan (actor)|William Duncan]] and [[Nell Shipman]] 1916 film within 24 hours.<ref name="MPW"/>
A number of [[Andy Hardy]] films starring [[Mickey Rooney]] were written by Johnston, among them ''[[The Hardys Ride High]]'', ''[[Life Begins for Andy Hardy]]'', ''[[The Courtship of Andy Hardy]]'', ''[[Andy Hardy's Double Life]]'' and ''[[Andy Hardy's Blonde Trouble]]''. Her other films included the coming-of-age comedy ''[[Seventeen (1940 film)|Seventeen]]'', the romantic comedy ''[[Janie (1944 film)|Janie]]'' and its sequel, ''[[Janie Gets Married]]'', plus the 1946 adaptation of the classic ''[[Black Beauty (1946 film)|Black Beauty]]''.
She also wrote the screenplays for a 1946 musical comedy, ''[[The Time, the Place and the Girl (1946 film)|The Time, the Place and the Girl]]'' and the 1948 film ''[[Stage Struck (1948 film)|Stage Struck]]''.
Johnston died in [[San Diego, California]] in 1978.
